# 🔵 GET Method

Used to retrieve data from the server.

### Example

```http id="hm4"
GET /students
```

Spring Boot:

```java id="hm5"
@GetMapping("/students")
public String getStudents() {
    return "Student List";
}
```

Response:

```json id="hm6"
[
  {
    "id": 1,
    "name": "Anup"
  }
]
```

### Characteristics

* Safe ✅
* Idempotent ✅
* No Request Body

---

# 🟢 POST Method

Used to create a new resource.

### Example

```http id="hm7"
POST /students
```

Request Body:

```json id="hm8"
{
  "name": "Anup",
  "age": 21
}
```

Spring Boot:

```java id="hm9"
@PostMapping("/students")
public String saveStudent() {
    return "Student Saved";
}
```

### Characteristics

* Safe ❌
* Idempotent ❌
* Request Body Required

---

# 🟡 PUT Method

Used to completely update an existing resource.

### Example

```http id="hm10"
PUT /students/1
```

Request Body:

```json id="hm11"
{
  "name": "Anup Kumar",
  "age": 22
}
```

Spring Boot:

```java id="hm12"
@PutMapping("/students/{id}")
public String updateStudent(
        @PathVariable int id) {

    return "Updated";
}
```

### Characteristics

* Safe ❌
* Idempotent ✅

---

# 🟠 PATCH Method

Used to partially update a resource.

### Example

```http id="hm13"
PATCH /students/1
```

Request Body:

```json id="hm14"
{
  "age": 22
}
```

Spring Boot:

```java id="hm15"
@PatchMapping("/students/{id}")
public String updateAge() {
    return "Age Updated";
}
```

### Characteristics

* Safe ❌
* Idempotent Usually ✅

---

# 🔴 DELETE Method

Used to remove a resource.

### Example

```http id="hm16"
DELETE /students/1
```

Spring Boot:

```java id="hm17"
@DeleteMapping("/students/{id}")
public String deleteStudent() {
    return "Deleted";
}
```

### Characteristics

* Safe ❌
* Idempotent ✅

---

# 🟣 HEAD Method

Similar to GET but returns only headers.

No response body is returned.

Example:

```http id="hm18"
HEAD /students
```

Uses:

* Check Resource Availability
* Check File Size
* Verify Last Modified Time

---

# ⚫ OPTIONS Method

Returns supported HTTP methods.

Example:

```http id="hm19"
OPTIONS /students
```

Response:

```text id="hm20"
Allow:
GET, POST, PUT, DELETE
```

---

# 🔘 TRACE Method

Used for diagnostic purposes.

```http id="hm21"
TRACE /students
```

Rarely used in modern applications.

---

# ⚪ CONNECT Method

Creates a network tunnel.

Mostly used with HTTPS proxies.

```http id="hm22"
CONNECT server.example.com:443
```

---

# 📊 HTTP Methods Summary

| Method  | CRUD                  | Safe | Idempotent |
| ------- | --------------------- | ---- | ---------- |
| GET     | Read                  | ✅    | ✅          |
| POST    | Create                | ❌    | ❌          |
| PUT     | Update                | ❌    | ✅          |
| PATCH   | Partial Update        | ❌    | Usually ✅  |
| DELETE  | Delete                | ❌    | ✅          |
| HEAD    | Read Headers          | ✅    | ✅          |
| OPTIONS | Get Supported Methods | ✅    | ✅          |
| TRACE   | Diagnostic            | ✅    | ✅          |
| CONNECT | Tunnel                | ❌    | ❌          |

---

# 🏷 Safe Methods

Safe methods do not modify server data.

Examples:

```text id="hm23"
GET

HEAD

OPTIONS
```

---

# 🏷 Idempotent Methods

Calling the method multiple times produces the same result.

Example:

```text id="hm24"
PUT

DELETE

GET
```

